\subsection{Curvature and rehybridzation}
The carbon network on graphene is planar, and thus forms $sp^2$ hybridization with orthogonal $\sigma$ and $\pi$ orbitals [Fig.~\ref{fig:cartoon}(a)]. In contrast, the carbon atoms on the CNT surface lie on a curved surface, and thus the $\sigma$ bonds are pyramidalized, and the $\pi$ orbitals bend [Fig.~\ref{fig:cartoon}(b)]. Therefore, unlike in planar graphene, the $\sigma$ and $\pi$ orbitals are no longer perpendicular to each other. As a consequence the parts of the of the $\pi$ orbitals outside and inside rearrange due to Coulomb repulsion, and the outer contribution is much larger than the inner one [Fig.~\ref{fig:cartoon}(b)]. These lead to mixing of $\sigma$ and $\pi$ orbitals, which is known as rehybridization, and crucially depends on the nanotube diameter and chirality. The rehybridization leads to bonding which is in between $sp^2$ and $sp^3$, and can be recognized as $sp^{2+\tau}$ hybridization (where $\tau$ lies within 0 and 1, depending on the tube diameter and chirality).~\cite{Haddon17091993, Dumitrica2002182}



